TOML MANIFEST STYLE RULES (the design guide §6 + §7.12):
1. PRESCRIPTIVE: MUST / MUST NOT / OK pattern / ERROR pattern. No prose
   "because", no "if possible", no "preferably".
2. PATTERN ORIENTED: 3-7 "pattern" examples with note "(do not copy
   literally: replace with the query terms)".
3. NO REPETITIONS: do NOT duplicate USAGE + ARG NAMES, do NOT repeat
   "Example: X" after every rule, do NOT repeat OUTPUT in description +
   schema_inline.
4. COMPACT: max 25 words/sentence. Inline backticks (`top=5`) not
   "Example: top=5". No redundant bullets. IT/EN parallel, not
   identical-translated.

description CONSTRAINTS — HEAD ONLY §2.5 (UNIVERSAL RULE):
- Single string, NO newline (TOML manifest). NO Python jargon.
- EXACTLY 4 chapters in this order, terse and pattern-oriented:
  SCOPO: <1 sentence: what it does>. PATTERN: <literal call: name(arg="...", arg=N)>. NON: <anti-pattern + disambiguation vs sibling tools>. OUT: <pipeable output shape>.
- HEAD ONLY: the description is ONLY these 4 chapters. FORBIDDEN the implementation tail (strip-tags, caps, backend, User-Agent, headers...): it lives in the code, NOT here. The machine reads only the head.
- HARD LIMITS: head (start->OUT:) <= {{ head_max }} char; whole description <= {{ desc_max }} char. Beyond = you're writing tail, cut it.
- SCOPO+PATTERN front-loaded (the proposer reads them). The §2.2 verb boundary goes in NON: (e.g. "NON directories -> delete_dirs").

